cs.CG, cs.DM, cs.DS, cs.GT, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with a problem in computational geometry, specifically the study of line arrangements and their properties. This makes cs.CG the most likely sub-category. The problem also involves combinatorial aspects, such as the characterization of matchings, which suggests cs.DM and cs.DS as likely sub-categories. The paper also uses graph theory and optimization techniques, which could place it in cs.GT. Finally, the problem has applications in information theory and communication networks, which could make cs.SI a relevant sub-category.
